{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"[PASS 1 — T1 Prior-art / novel-architecture justification] Verdict: PASS (overlay fired; well-grounded). One minor coaching item.\n\nThis plan crosses several T1 bright-lines (novel cross-cutting architecture, security/auth signing, a content-addressed cache, portability/concurrency target) so the overlay applies — and the plan handles it unusually well.\n\nAFFIRMATIONS (criteria satisfied — positive feedback, not findings):\n- T1(a) prior art is considered before committing: the parent \"Context\"/\"What\" explicitly grounds the design against Gitaly, Sourcegraph gitserver/zoekt, GitHub tarball API, Bazel, ccache, Nix, and in-toto; the janitor child (b73c) cites Bazel's move-GC-to-idle and the kernel-guarantee posture of Gitaly/Sourcegraph/Bazel/ccache as the basis for rejecting a PID+heartbeat lease. This is real, named, load-bearing prior art — not reinvention.\n- T1(b) novelty justified vs an established approach: the rejected alternatives are explicit and captured in an ADR (PID+heartbeat lease rejected from a spike as \"unsound: N readers, PID reuse, crash-stale\"; payload-schema SHA binding rejected in favor of the manifest channel; `git archive` rejected for read-tree+checkout-index on concrete faithfulness grounds — export-ignore drops, submodule omission, LFS pointer files, export-subst rewrite). S4b (e308) carries an explicit Rule-of-Three / YAGNI check (\"exactly two consumers today ... justified by the divergence risk ... de-risked by an explicit back-out\") for the shared ref-resolution boundary. Anti-repackaging discipline is satisfied.\n- T1(c) capability assertions largely resolved: `git archive` lossiness, `uploadpack.allowReachableSHA1InWant` (with a \"fetch a containing ref then resolve\" fallback), `--filter=blob:none`, POSIX delete-on-last-close, the relatime/noatime atime caveat (use mtime touch-on-read instead), and the EFS/NFS flock caveat (tracked on alto-fruit-punch, with an atomic-mkdir fallback) are all stated with fallbacks/limits rather than left as bare \"library supports X\" assertions.\n\nFINDING (minor — capability assertion partially unresolved):\n- [ ] Validate the \"in-toto Statement → DSSE/asymmetric envelope swap\" forward-path claim with a concrete shape, not just a contract test. (criteria: T1(c) unverified capability assertions resolved. location: S4 `ill-hazel-probe` (30b3) \"What\" — \"Shape the manifest pin so a future move to DSSE + asymmetric + transparency log is an envelope swap, not a rewrite (KEEP HMAC now)\" + AC6; parent \"What\" attested bullet. evidence: the claim that a later DSSE/asymmetric/transparency-log migration is \"an envelope swap, not a rewrite\" is the one prior-art-derived capability assertion that is asserted rather than demonstrated — the pin currently rides the HMAC manifest-step channel (`verified-at-sha:<sha>` as a manifest list element), whereas an in-toto Statement is a structured JSON predicate/subject; whether a manifest-step string can be re-homed into a DSSE Statement \"without changing the pin's data shape\" is load-bearing for the no-rewrite claim and is not shown. AC6 asks for \"a test/contract\" on the data shape, which is good, but does not pin down WHAT the in-toto subject/predicate fields are.) suggested_fix: In S4 (30b3), add a one-line concrete sketch of the in-toto Statement subject/predicate the pin maps to (e.g. subject = {name: ticket_id, digest: {sha1: <verified_at_sha>}}, predicateType = the verdict), so the \"envelope swap not rewrite\" claim is demonstrably grounded in the in-toto v1 schema rather than asserted — and the AC6 contract test asserts against that named shape.\n\nNet: T1 is satisfied. The plan's prior-art grounding and rejected-alternatives discipline are a model for the rubric; the single finding above is a polish item on one forward-compatibility capability claim, not a blocker."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782531274434956001,"uuid":"13dd0186-74bb-4f16-80a3-6da99844650c"}